1339	\section{\(\otimes\)-invertibility and the commutative-monoid group-law engine}
1340	\label{sec:tensorobj_invertibility}
1341	
1342	The relative Picard group law is assembled from \emph{\(\otimes\)-invertibility}
1343	and the monoidal coherence isomorphisms of
1344	\cref{lem:tensorobj_assoc_iso,lem:tensorobj_unit_iso,lem:tensorobj_comm_iso},
1345	following Mathlib's Picard-group idiom (\(\mathtt{Module.Invertible}\),
1346	\(\mathtt{CommRing.Pic} = \mathrm{Units}(\mathrm{Skeleton}(\mathtt{ModuleCat}\,R))\),
1347	\(\mathtt{instCommGroupPic}\); \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup}) as the
1348	design template. The inverse of an invertible object is carried by the predicate
1349	itself, so neither the open-immersion restriction-compatibility isomorphism
1350	\cref{lem:tensorobj_restrict_iso} nor a separate tensor-inverse lemma is on the
1351	critical path.
